00:06:09.350 --> 00:06:13.780
Scribely actually did a study
on this that we released

00:06:13.780 --> 00:06:17.570
for the last Global Accessibility
Awareness Day a few months back

00:06:17.570 --> 00:06:19.350
in 2023.

00:06:19.350 --> 00:06:21.700
And I really wanted to
collect some research on this

00:06:21.700 --> 00:06:26.080
because I kind of had this unproven
theory that it's a whole lot worse

00:06:26.080 --> 00:06:30.050
than what we're seeing from other
statistics about alt text out there,

00:06:30.050 --> 00:06:37.290
like the WebAIM Million
study that says about 58.2%

00:06:37.290 --> 00:06:39.360
of home pages are missing alt text.

00:06:39.360 --> 00:06:41.610
I was seeing a lot more than that.

00:06:41.610 --> 00:06:46.980
So we did this study to collect data
on how much alt text is out there.

00:06:46.980 --> 00:06:48.152
And what we found is,

00:06:48.153 --> 00:06:51.110
not a single company
currently possesses a homepage

00:06:51.110 --> 00:06:54.090
with content that is fully
accessible, meaning there was

00:06:54.090 --> 00:06:57.660
at least one error that we
found with images and videos.

00:06:57.660 --> 00:07:01.480
And this is the top 100
E-commerce providers

00:07:01.480 --> 00:07:04.140
in terms of their popularity
and search results.

00:07:05.480 --> 00:07:08.270
Here are a few other stats that
I'm putting up on the slide.

00:07:08.270 --> 00:07:12.291
For homepages,
27 had some descriptive alt text,

00:07:12.292 --> 00:07:17.620
only one had meaningful and
descriptive alt text for all images.

00:07:17.620 --> 00:07:22.140
For product pages, the situation
was much, much worse with alt text.

00:07:22.140 --> 00:07:26.060
97% had inaccurate, incomplete,
or missing alt text,

00:07:26.060 --> 00:07:29.460
and only one had high-quality
alt text for every image.

00:07:29.460 --> 00:07:34.130
So most of the product alt text
that we were finding was formulaic.

00:07:35.600 --> 00:07:39.620
For social media, 12% of accounts
had descriptive alt text on Twitter,

00:07:39.620 --> 00:07:43.260
and 3% had a descriptive
alt text on Instagram.

00:07:43.260 --> 00:07:46.940
I think the difference there
might be because of the Twitter

00:07:46.940 --> 00:07:51.080
or X alt button that was implemented,
where you can actually see

00:07:51.080 --> 00:07:53.240
when alt text has been
added for an image.

00:07:54.740 --> 00:07:58.840
So you can check out more results
from this study on the Scribely blog.

00:07:58.840 --> 00:08:01.580
But I wanted to put that up
here just so you can get a sense

00:08:01.580 --> 00:08:06.440
of what we're looking at right
now in 2023 for companies

00:08:06.440 --> 00:08:09.634
that have actually arguably
higher budgets than most

00:08:09.635 --> 00:08:10.900
to handle this work.

00:08:12.390 --> 00:08:16.850
So we have to ask ourselves,
what's the hold up here?

00:08:16.850 --> 00:08:19.260
A few possible reasons that
I'd like to go through.

00:08:19.260 --> 00:08:21.420
The first could be awareness.

00:08:21.420 --> 00:08:24.660
It's possible, I guess,
but most should know

00:08:24.661 --> 00:08:26.820
about alt text at this point.

00:08:26.820 --> 00:08:30.240
It gets a lot of stage time
at conferences, marketing,

00:08:30.240 --> 00:08:34.480
accessibility-related conferences
, and there's a lot of visibility

00:08:34.480 --> 00:08:36.230
into this accessibility
requirement.

00:08:37.350 --> 00:08:38.350
Expertise.

00:08:39.270 --> 00:08:41.660
Alt text,
pretty searchable at this point.

00:08:41.660 --> 00:08:43.980
There are a lot of guides
and tutorials walking through

00:08:43.980 --> 00:08:45.760
how to do this exactly.

00:08:45.760 --> 00:08:48.120
So I think there's a lot
of information and ways

00:08:48.120 --> 00:08:49.610
to develop expertise out there.

00:08:50.850 --> 00:08:55.150
Technology could be another
reason, kind of an excuse.

00:08:55.150 --> 00:08:58.190
But most platforms have alt
text fields at this point,

00:08:58.190 --> 00:09:00.600
so there is a place to
actually place the alt text.

00:09:01.960 --> 00:09:02.950
Budget.

00:09:02.950 --> 00:09:04.700
This is a big one.

00:09:04.700 --> 00:09:07.800
Yes, there are budget
concerns, but you know what?

00:09:07.800 --> 00:09:13.130
There is money to be found for
website copy, SEO, social media.

00:09:13.130 --> 00:09:16.690
Can kind of argue the case that alt
text should be included there, too.

00:09:18.080 --> 00:09:19.020
Time.

00:09:19.020 --> 00:09:23.160
Certainly, alt text does take time,
but I'd also like to point out

00:09:23.160 --> 00:09:26.120
that a lot of things
that matters take time,

00:09:26.120 --> 00:09:28.320
and alt text is
definitely one of them.

00:09:28.320 --> 00:09:32.800
So all possible reasons why
there might be a hold up here.

00:09:32.800 --> 00:09:37.730
My own personal theory that's totally
opinionated is people don't like

00:09:37.730 --> 00:09:39.200
to write more than they have to.

00:09:40.870 --> 00:09:42.740
But who really wants to admit
that, right?

00:09:42.740 --> 00:09:45.770
So take it with a grain of salt
on the whole writing thing,

00:09:45.770 --> 00:09:51.300
but it might offer some reasons
why ChatGPT has become so popular.

00:09:51.300 --> 00:09:56.660
It's just this barrier to writing
that a lot of us experience.

00:09:57.870 --> 00:10:01.700
So whatever the reason may be,
the fact of the matter is many

00:10:01.700 --> 00:10:06.430
of the top organizations today
are using some form of automation

00:10:06.430 --> 00:10:08.920
to manage the alt
text for their images.

00:10:08.920 --> 00:10:12.930
And that's surprising because they
do potentially have higher budgets

00:10:12.930 --> 00:10:14.770
for this type of work.

00:10:14.770 --> 00:10:19.020
But I'd like to point out that taking
shortcuts doesn't change the rules

00:10:19.020 --> 00:10:20.980
when it comes to accessibility.

00:10:20.980 --> 00:10:23.190
Auto or AI-generated
alt text still needs

00:10:23.190 --> 00:10:27.430
to provide that equivalent
text alternative for the image.

00:10:27.430 --> 00:10:31.630
So these automated text,
they're missing the mark still.

00:10:33.020 --> 00:10:41.020
OK, so part one is, how exactly
do we tackle writing equivalent

00:10:41.530 --> 00:10:42.900
text alternatives?

00:10:42.900 --> 00:10:45.090
This is pretty much the
main point of alt text,

00:10:45.090 --> 00:10:47.720
so I felt like it was
important to start here.

00:10:47.720 --> 00:10:50.530
Most shortcuts that are
available for alt text

00:10:50.530 --> 00:10:53.970
don't actually help you do
that, and this is problematic

00:10:53.970 --> 00:10:55.270
for accessibility reasons.

00:10:55.270 --> 00:10:57.780
So we're going to start
this session off with,

00:10:57.780 --> 00:11:01.590
How exactly can we write alt text?
And I'm going to try

00:11:01.590 --> 00:11:04.020
to stay away from the basics
because there are a lot

00:11:04.020 --> 00:11:05.410
of tutorials out there.

00:11:05.410 --> 00:11:09.610
So let's get into it: alt
text beyond the basics.

00:11:09.610 --> 00:11:13.260
My definition for alt text is
a short, meaningful description

00:11:13.260 --> 00:11:15.470
that captures the why of an image.

00:11:15.470 --> 00:11:17.970
Now, a lot of people
focus on the short part,

00:11:17.970 --> 00:11:21.580
and I'd really like to underline
and highlight the meaningful part

00:11:21.580 --> 00:11:25.980
because that's really the essence
of what it takes to write alt text

00:11:25.980 --> 00:11:29.710
that actually makes images
interesting and distinctive,

00:11:29.710 --> 00:11:32.720
and we're getting to
those unique details.

00:11:32.720 --> 00:11:33.790
Also, character count.

00:11:33.790 --> 00:11:37.460
Big question, and there are a
lot of arguments to be made.

00:11:37.460 --> 00:11:40.600
Sometimes there are platform
limitations, but generally speaking,

00:11:40.600 --> 00:11:44.270
Scribely recommends less than
250 characters to write alt text.

00:11:46.590 --> 00:11:51.170
I'm going to walk you through
the actual formula that we follow

00:11:51.170 --> 00:11:54.740
for writing image
descriptions at Scribely.

00:11:54.740 --> 00:11:56.950
So this is an answer to the
question, What’s the secret

00:11:56.950 --> 00:12:01.110
to writing great alt text?
First up, there's a lot of work

00:12:01.110 --> 00:12:04.080
that happens before you
actually write anything at all.

00:12:04.080 --> 00:12:06.110
The first is to analyze context.

00:12:06.110 --> 00:12:10.600
So that's everything surrounding
the image, including text, images,

00:12:10.600 --> 00:12:14.680
the page, the audience, you
know, really anything cultural,

00:12:14.680 --> 00:12:17.310
details that might be important,
that might be factoring in.

00:12:17.310 --> 00:12:18.650
Think about context.

00:12:20.280 --> 00:12:21.860
Next up, we have purpose.

00:12:21.860 --> 00:12:25.420
Think about the role that the
image plays for the audience.

00:12:25.420 --> 00:12:27.490
Why is the image there
in the first place?

00:12:27.490 --> 00:12:28.870
Why was it selected?

00:12:28.870 --> 00:12:30.330
What role is it playing?

00:12:31.810 --> 00:12:34.210
Finally, meaning as step three.

00:12:34.210 --> 00:12:36.680
Message the image
sends to the audience.

00:12:36.680 --> 00:12:39.890
So if this image could
talk, what would it say?

00:12:39.890 --> 00:12:43.050
It might say something like,
Look at this, buy the thing,

00:12:43.050 --> 00:12:45.270
or like me as an image, something.

00:12:45.270 --> 00:12:47.070
It’s trying to tell you something.

00:12:47.070 --> 00:12:50.020
Decode that message and that might
help you write your alt text.

00:12:51.370 --> 00:12:54.020
This also, I think,
really helps with writer's block.

00:12:54.020 --> 00:12:58.640
So I recommend not skipping this
pre-work if you are struggling

00:12:58.640 --> 00:13:00.350
to get started
writing your alt text.

00:13:01.900 --> 00:13:05.540
When you're ready to write and you've
gone through those pre-work steps,

00:13:05.540 --> 00:13:09.140
the question is, what is the
best way to structure alt text?

00:13:09.140 --> 00:13:11.470
And there is a formula
for this as well.

00:13:12.600 --> 00:13:15.582
First up, I always recommend
identifying the image

00:13:15.583 --> 00:13:16.810
in some sort of way.

00:13:16.810 --> 00:13:21.660
So this helps the user immediately
visualize the right information.

00:13:21.660 --> 00:13:22.510
Is it a painting?

00:13:22.510 --> 00:13:23.220
Is it a chart?

00:13:23.220 --> 00:13:24.590
Is it a graph?

00:13:24.590 --> 00:13:27.140
That can really happen right
away so we can get people

00:13:27.140 --> 00:13:31.040
in the right headspace to imagine
the descriptive details after that.

00:13:31.040 --> 00:13:32.880
The only exception
to this is photos.

00:13:32.880 --> 00:13:34.770
You don't need to say
photo of or image of.

00:13:36.060 --> 00:13:39.210
After identifying, think about
what is the focus of this image

00:13:39.210 --> 00:13:40.820
or the main subject.

00:13:40.820 --> 00:13:45.320
Now this could be a person, a place,
an object, an artistic effect.

00:13:45.320 --> 00:13:48.310
What is coming through as the
most important visual detail?

00:13:48.310 --> 00:13:50.080
Where did your eye go first?

00:13:50.080 --> 00:13:51.680
That's often where the focus is.

00:13:52.790 --> 00:13:54.000
Then details.

00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:57.100
Think about the meaningful
and relevant details.

00:13:57.100 --> 00:13:58.160
So those are really important.

00:13:58.160 --> 00:14:02.230
You can't say everything and
keep it short, but you want

00:14:02.230 --> 00:14:04.410
to think about what
makes that image unique,

00:14:04.410 --> 00:14:06.210
and what details you'll
need to include there.

00:14:07.600 --> 00:14:08.790
Finally, read it back.

00:14:08.790 --> 00:14:11.520
Does the alt text sufficiently
describe the image?

00:14:11.520 --> 00:14:14.840
Did you actually provide
a text equivalent,

00:14:14.840 --> 00:14:16.780
or do you need more description?

