But we're going to go through image
recognition with confidence scores.

00:28:58.170 --> 00:29:03.230
This is an approach computer vision
plus natural language processing

00:29:03.230 --> 00:29:05.200
and combinations thereof.

00:29:05.200 --> 00:29:08.410
And then finally,
multimodal and large language models.

00:29:09.930 --> 00:29:13.650
So first up, we have image
recognition and scores.

00:29:13.650 --> 00:29:16.250
This is a really common
approach seen across a lot

00:29:16.250 --> 00:29:18.580
of computer vision tools out there.

00:29:18.580 --> 00:29:21.960
And the way that it works is it
identifies objects, places, people,

00:29:21.960 --> 00:29:26.320
text, anything it can identify
within the image actions.

00:29:26.320 --> 00:29:31.250
And it attempts to label
those, often with just a word

00:29:31.250 --> 00:29:34.380
or a few words, and then
apply a confidence score about

00:29:34.380 --> 00:29:39.360
how certain it is that that
thing is what it actually is.

00:29:39.360 --> 00:29:44.820
So you get this view into what
we have up here on the screen.

00:29:44.820 --> 00:29:49.550
This is a photo of a person
with some green boxes drawn

00:29:49.550 --> 00:29:53.210
around different parts of the photo,
and they really have this kind

00:29:53.210 --> 00:29:56.680
of interesting outfit with
striped pants, a leather vest,

00:29:56.680 --> 00:30:00.120
and a yellow sequined
button-down top.

00:30:00.120 --> 00:30:03.790
So very stylish, but the
bounding boxes that we're seeing

00:30:03.790 --> 00:30:07.700
are the actual components of the
photo that can be recognized.

00:30:07.700 --> 00:30:12.130
So we see here,
pants, 96% confident.

00:30:12.130 --> 00:30:16.370
Footwear appears twice because
there are two shoes in view.

00:30:16.370 --> 00:30:20.770
One at 92%, one at 85% confidence.

00:30:20.770 --> 00:30:25.890
It has 86% confidence in a person,
and 74% confidence in a belt.

00:30:25.890 --> 00:30:29.380
So it's attempting to see
what's in this image based on

00:30:29.380 --> 00:30:30.380
how it's been trained.

00:30:31.720 --> 00:30:38.590
The top providers that are using this
model are Google Cloud Vision API.

00:30:38.590 --> 00:30:41.340
If you want to test this
out, you can drop any image

00:30:41.340 --> 00:30:44.330
into Google Cloud Vision
API, which is how I was able

00:30:44.330 --> 00:30:47.180
to get some of the examples that
are featured in this presentation,

00:30:47.180 --> 00:30:48.180
and test it out.

00:30:49.200 --> 00:30:51.850
It looks for all sorts of things.

00:30:51.850 --> 00:30:58.430
It uses face and landmark
detection, OCR, object localization,

00:30:58.430 --> 00:31:00.810
explicit content flags.

00:31:00.810 --> 00:31:03.520
That's what it's designed for; to
actually see what's in the image.

00:31:04.580 --> 00:31:08.540
Amazon Rekognition is another
one, similarly looking for objects

00:31:08.540 --> 00:31:13.180
and scenes and activities, but also,
interestingly enough, celebrities.

00:31:13.180 --> 00:31:15.470
That's a key part of
Amazon Rekognition

00:31:15.471 --> 00:31:18.130
and the way that it's useful
and has been trained.

00:31:19.220 --> 00:31:20.180
Clearfy [phonetic]

00:31:20.180 --> 00:31:21.150
is another big one.

00:31:21.150 --> 00:31:23.990
It identifies concepts in images.

00:31:23.990 --> 00:31:28.480
And it's trained in over 10,000
concepts and 20 million images.

00:31:28.480 --> 00:31:31.800
So it's looking for
objects, themes, moods,

00:31:31.800 --> 00:31:34.490
which may yield a different
result than the others.

00:31:36.040 --> 00:31:37.950
So thoughts on this approach.

00:31:37.950 --> 00:31:41.220
I think it's useful for
object ID and keywording.

00:31:41.220 --> 00:31:45.170
So actually finding
objects within images

00:31:45.170 --> 00:31:48.090
that the information
contained there.

00:31:48.090 --> 00:31:50.260
We can get some really
good details and keywords

00:31:50.260 --> 00:31:52.290
for search results this way.

00:31:53.350 --> 00:31:57.120
But I think it's difficult to
visualize a list of words, right?

00:31:57.120 --> 00:31:59.440
We have this list of
words, and it is

00:31:59.440 --> 00:32:01.509
maybe identifying
everything appropriately,

00:32:01.510 --> 00:32:02.920
but we still don't understand

00:32:02.920 --> 00:32:06.680
what's there, and we're
missing some critical details

00:32:06.680 --> 00:32:08.690
on how everything
stitches together.

00:32:08.690 --> 00:32:13.530
It's seeing pants and belt,
but the whole ensemble

00:32:13.530 --> 00:32:17.260
that guy wearing was really
quite cool, and it's missing all

00:32:17.260 --> 00:32:21.000
of those fun, unique visual
details contained within the image.

00:32:23.480 --> 00:32:27.970
I am not feeling all that
confident in the confidence scores,

00:32:27.970 --> 00:32:28.950
just in my review.

00:32:28.950 --> 00:32:31.050
I'm interested to hear
others' thoughts there.

00:32:31.050 --> 00:32:35.070
I don't know how these
confidence scores are determined,

00:32:35.070 --> 00:32:37.590
but they seem to be a
bit all over the place.

00:32:37.590 --> 00:32:42.130
So there's some distrust in
the confidence scores there.

00:32:43.580 --> 00:32:47.970
Here's another example, and I'm
going to use this image again.

00:32:47.970 --> 00:32:49.520
We're going to see it a few times,

00:32:49.520 --> 00:32:53.460
just as an example
for this AI section.

00:32:53.460 --> 00:32:55.140
So I’m going to describe it.

00:32:55.140 --> 00:32:58.000
It's a portrait of a person
wearing a pastel-colored wig

00:32:58.000 --> 00:33:00.660
and bold red and orange eye
makeup, looking at us

00:33:00.660 --> 00:33:04.730
with a mysterious expression
