00:34:00.250 --> 00:34:02.970
out of this particular approach.

00:34:04.590 --> 00:34:08.190
All right, so the next approach
is computer vision plus

00:34:08.190 --> 00:34:11.670
natural language processing,
or some sort of combination

00:34:11.670 --> 00:34:13.480
of those technologies.

00:34:13.480 --> 00:34:17.010
And this is AI-generated
human-like image description.

00:34:17.010 --> 00:34:20.450
So we're moving beyond word list
and we're actually attempting

00:34:20.450 --> 00:34:22.050
to create sentences.

00:34:22.050 --> 00:34:25.950
I'm not an AI expert, but I want
to quickly define these terms.

00:34:25.950 --> 00:34:27.290
So we all know what they are.

00:34:27.290 --> 00:34:31.840
Computer vision enables computers
to derive information from images,

00:34:31.840 --> 00:34:33.990
videos, and other inputs.

00:34:33.990 --> 00:34:37.800
Natural language processing is
about how computers interpret

00:34:37.800 --> 00:34:40.690
and comprehend human language.

00:34:40.690 --> 00:34:44.560
And image captioning is kind of like
the intersection between these two.

00:34:44.560 --> 00:34:47.753
So the image is encoded
into different features

00:34:47.754 --> 00:34:52.120
that are recognized, and then
decoded into descriptive text.

00:34:52.120 --> 00:34:54.720
So we're actually attempting
to string words together

00:34:54.720 --> 00:34:59.400
to make interpretations, to try
to comprehend, and manipulate,

00:34:59.400 --> 00:35:03.300
and go a step further
into image description.

00:35:04.990 --> 00:35:07.750
So a few providers in this
space, MidJourney,

00:35:07.750 --> 00:35:12.230
doing some interesting things
with their describe command.

00:35:12.230 --> 00:35:17.130
I'm going to start throwing
out dates just to emphasize

00:35:17.130 --> 00:35:18.240
how recent all of this is.

00:35:18.240 --> 00:35:20.990
On April 4th, 2023,
they released the describe command,

00:35:20.990 --> 00:35:24.380
allowing users to transform
images into words,

00:35:24.380 --> 00:35:28.060
and actually reverse the process
of inputting text-based prompts

00:35:28.060 --> 00:35:29.540
to generate images.

00:35:29.540 --> 00:35:34.790
So the whole hypothesis is, Well,
can we use these image prompts

00:35:34.790 --> 00:35:39.710
for alt text purposes,
and can it go both ways?

00:35:39.710 --> 00:35:42.980
If we use this describe command
going from image to text,

00:35:42.980 --> 00:35:46.650
how can that recreate images,
and different versions of images?

00:35:46.650 --> 00:35:49.320
So this is a really interesting
approach happening right now

00:35:49.320 --> 00:35:53.680
where we're seeing more
details than before.

00:35:53.680 --> 00:35:57.870
So entering this command
creates an image-upload option.

00:35:57.870 --> 00:36:00.740
You upload your image
and then hitting enter

00:36:00.740 --> 00:36:04.690
returns four different versions of
a description based on that image.

00:36:04.690 --> 00:36:07.090
And then you can actually
use one of those versions

00:36:07.090 --> 00:36:09.960
to remix the image based
on that description.

00:36:09.960 --> 00:36:13.420
So MidJourney is helping us
create different versions

00:36:13.420 --> 00:36:19.670
of images utilizing AI,
but the possibilities

00:36:19.670 --> 00:36:23.150
for alt text here could
be interesting to explore.

00:36:24.820 --> 00:36:29.680
We also have Microsoft Azure
with their Vision AI caption

00:36:29.680 --> 00:36:31.930
and dense caption option.

00:36:31.930 --> 00:36:38.080
So the way this works is the AI
is attempting to recognize objects

00:36:38.080 --> 00:36:41.670
in images but also string them
together into some sort of sentence.

00:36:41.670 --> 00:36:46.100
So a caption returns a
very short description.

00:36:46.100 --> 00:36:53.140
Here, we have a yellow toy
bus with luggage on top

00:36:53.140 --> 00:36:55.650
that's kind of moving
across a pavement.

00:36:55.650 --> 00:36:59.980
And the image alt text is A toy bus
with luggage on top. So not bad.

00:36:59.980 --> 00:37:02.290
We could probably go
into more details here.

00:37:02.290 --> 00:37:05.480
I think there might be an
actual bus in the background

00:37:05.480 --> 00:37:08.330
that's blurred out in all
sorts of funky colors.

00:37:08.330 --> 00:37:12.250
We can get into the style of the
bus; it's more vintage-looking,

00:37:12.250 --> 00:37:15.330
but that's the description
they have for the caption.

00:37:15.330 --> 00:37:18.110
A then a dense caption
works in a different way.

00:37:18.110 --> 00:37:21.050
So it attempts to see all of
the different parts of the image

00:37:21.050 --> 00:37:24.220
and then write a short
caption for each one of those.

00:37:24.220 --> 00:37:27.490
So here we have an
aerial view of a bunch

00:37:27.490 --> 00:37:30.920
of different colored glasses
with different liquid inside.

00:37:30.920 --> 00:37:34.970
And it returns a whole scene
description at the top that,

00:37:34.971 --> 00:37:38.500
which is, A group of glasses
with different colored liquid.

00:37:38.500 --> 00:37:42.950
And it's recognizing that because
it sees a close up of the glass.

00:37:42.950 --> 00:37:45.970
A glass with pink liquid in
it, a glass with blue liquid,

00:37:45.970 --> 00:37:48.080
a glass of liquid on a saucer.

00:37:48.080 --> 00:37:49.710
It's attempting to see
all of these things

00:37:49.710 --> 00:37:52.990
and then string them together
for a whole scene description.

00:37:54.270 --> 00:37:58.170
And it's looking at up to
10 regions of the image.

00:37:58.170 --> 00:37:59.840
So a different approach
being taken here.

00:38:01.090 --> 00:38:03.570
And a few others using
this computer vision

00:38:03.570 --> 00:38:07.960
plus natural language processing
approach, CloudSide AI.

00:38:07.960 --> 00:38:11.150
They are labeling, classifying,
and moderating images

00:38:11.150 --> 00:38:13.950
to also deliver whole
scene descriptions.

00:38:13.950 --> 00:38:15.990
Meta AI for Facebook and Instagram.

00:38:17.480 --> 00:38:20.060
There is alt text that can
be automatically generated

00:38:20.061 --> 00:38:22.330
for the images
that you post there.

00:38:22.330 --> 00:38:27.100
Identifying activities, landmarks,
animals, locations, relative size

00:38:27.100 --> 00:38:28.440
of elements.

00:38:28.440 --> 00:38:30.450
They've been making some
effort to improve that

00:38:30.450 --> 00:38:35.750
and to also deliver descriptions that
sound like they have been written,

00:38:35.750 --> 00:38:37.480
not just list of words.

00:38:38.620 --> 00:38:40.680
Filestack Image Captioning.

00:38:40.680 --> 00:38:45.190
So this returns captions
as a synchronous operation

00:38:45.190 --> 00:38:48.970
when utilizing the API, by just
running this caption command.

00:38:48.970 --> 00:38:50.610
So a few different
approaches there.

00:38:52.460 --> 00:38:53.460
So thoughts.

00:38:54.660 --> 00:38:57.820
These generally keep alt
text short and succinct,

00:38:57.820 --> 00:39:00.190
but that's not always a good thing.

00:39:00.190 --> 00:39:02.240
Again, we're looking for meaning.

00:39:02.240 --> 00:39:04.320
The descriptions are
often incomplete.

00:39:04.320 --> 00:39:07.760
Because it's focusing so much on
what is the most important detail

00:39:07.760 --> 00:39:10.990
to convey, it’s not getting into
the territory of the relevant

00:39:10.990 --> 00:39:14.160
and meaningful details
that make alt text great.

00:39:15.330 --> 00:39:18.390
It also is not able to
describe images in context.

00:39:18.390 --> 00:39:19.510
I'm just taking a look at time.

00:39:19.510 --> 00:39:20.610
I want to make sure we have enough.

00:39:22.320 --> 00:39:25.327
Getting into probably the
most promising approach

00:39:25.328 --> 00:39:26.770
that we have right now,

00:39:26.770 --> 00:39:30.740
multimodal and large-language
models, and combining these.

00:39:30.740 --> 00:39:34.060
So multimodal is combining
different types of data inputs

00:39:34.060 --> 00:39:38.070
to create different
determinations, draw conclusions.

00:39:38.070 --> 00:39:43.380
And by multiple types, I mean
images, voice, text, all kind of part

00:39:43.380 --> 00:39:46.394
of the same conversation
you're having,

00:39:46.395 --> 00:39:48.880
the way you're engaging with AI.

00:39:48.880 --> 00:39:52.740
And these are trained on
massive data sets that are aimed

00:39:52.740 --> 00:39:55.309
at recognizing, translating,
and generating text

00:39:55.310 --> 00:39:56.620
in a human-like fashion.

00:39:56.620 --> 00:39:59.660
So how is this progressing here?

00:39:59.660 --> 00:40:05.930
We have ChatGPT this week
announcing multimodal capabilities

00:40:05.930 --> 00:40:10.120
in ChatGPT for plus
and enterprise users.

00:40:10.120 --> 00:40:14.300
So soon people will be
able to input text, voice,

00:40:14.300 --> 00:40:19.650
and image prompts into ChatGPT
and have a conversation.

00:40:19.650 --> 00:40:22.440
And this is where we get
into prompt engineering,

00:40:22.440 --> 00:40:25.860
where you're fine-tuning these
questions that you're asking

00:40:25.860 --> 00:40:27.910
in order to get different results.

00:40:27.910 --> 00:40:31.100
You can actually test this
right now in Bing Chat,

00:40:31.100 --> 00:40:33.290
this multimodal capability.

00:40:33.290 --> 00:40:34.730
So I encourage you to do that.

