00:43:23.370 --> 00:43:28.600
We do use alt text on any
images that are important part

00:43:28.600 --> 00:43:34.050
of the context of the text or
graphics with data or info in them.

00:43:36.380 --> 00:43:38.850
 <v Caroline> OK,
and what's the question?

00:43:39.860 --> 00:43:43.470
 <v Laura> When is alt text required?
 <v Caroline> Oh, OK.

00:43:43.470 --> 00:43:47.590
So alt text is required when it
carries any visual information

00:43:47.590 --> 00:43:50.510
that is important for
a user to understand.

00:43:50.510 --> 00:43:55.230
So when we are talking about the
details of a chart, or graph,

00:43:55.230 --> 00:44:00.200
or the trend lines, all of that is
important to include in alt text.

00:44:00.200 --> 00:44:03.200
It's also important to pay
attention to any surrounding text.

00:44:03.200 --> 00:44:06.160
If anything's already been
explained in the caption

00:44:06.160 --> 00:44:09.180
or the surrounding text, you don't
need to repeat that information.

00:44:09.180 --> 00:44:12.360
Just think of the way the image
is furthering the surrounding text

00:44:12.360 --> 00:44:13.230
around it.

00:44:14.020 --> 00:44:14.650
 <v Laura> All right.

00:44:14.650 --> 00:44:15.050
Dee [phonetic]

00:44:15.050 --> 00:44:19.880
asked: On a team page with an image
gallery, do you include the name

00:44:19.880 --> 00:44:22.860
of the team members
in the alt text?

00:44:22.860 --> 00:44:24.200
 <v Caroline> It depends.

00:44:24.200 --> 00:44:27.710
Does their name appear
below their image?

00:44:27.710 --> 00:44:31.830
Or is their image truly the only
way that you would know their name?

00:44:33.150 --> 00:44:36.848
So I think that's an important
contextual piece of information

00:44:36.849 --> 00:44:38.080
to answer.

00:44:39.670 --> 00:44:43.270
If their name is displayed
below and just be read twice,

00:44:43.270 --> 00:44:45.360
it may not be necessary to include.

00:44:46.450 --> 00:44:50.720
 <v Laura> If you go back to
Peter Ingersoll's presentation,

00:44:50.720 --> 00:44:53.910
he had a picture of himself,
and he did a great alt text

00:44:53.910 --> 00:44:57.580
of describing him,
a 60 year old white man with a smile

00:44:57.580 --> 00:44:58.930
on his face kind of thing.

00:44:58.930 --> 00:45:00.820
And then he put his
name in the caption.

00:45:00.820 --> 00:45:04.720
So yes, like you said,
if the name is under the picture,

00:45:04.720 --> 00:45:06.710
then you don't need to
have it in that alt text.

00:45:06.710 --> 00:45:07.710
So that's good.

00:45:08.890 --> 00:45:13.180
Anonymous asked: Just
curious which role or roles

00:45:13.180 --> 00:45:15.727
on a web team is
generally responsible

00:45:15.728 --> 00:45:17.490
for creating the alt text,

00:45:17.490 --> 00:45:21.380
such as a site owner, the content
creator, the web developer?

00:45:22.414 --> 00:45:23.694
 <v Caroline> Yes.

00:45:24.030 --> 00:45:27.720
It often lands with different
teams, but I say that it should go

00:45:27.720 --> 00:45:31.240
with the person or the team
that is closest to the content.

00:45:31.240 --> 00:45:35.850
So that depends on the
organization, but we definitely need

00:45:35.850 --> 00:45:38.630
to have writers in this role.

00:45:38.630 --> 00:45:41.750
You have to love to write to
appreciate alt text, love the way

00:45:41.750 --> 00:45:44.070
that language and
communication work.

00:45:45.130 --> 00:45:47.900
So it’s really something I
think belongs with the team

00:45:47.900 --> 00:45:51.260
that's involved in selecting those
images or placing those images

00:45:51.260 --> 00:45:56.090
on the page, because they have a
really good reason for that why.

00:45:56.090 --> 00:45:58.410
Why does this image exist?

